const QUESTIONS_CRISC_C3 = [
  { id:40501, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which risk response involves eliminating the activity that gives rise to the risk?", options:["Risk avoidance, by discontinuing the process or activity creating the exposure entirely","Risk transfer, by shifting the financial impact of the exposure to another party","Risk acceptance, by acknowledging the exposure and taking no further action at all overall","Risk mitigation, by implementing controls that reduce the likelihood of the event"], correct:0, explanation:"Avoidance removes the source activity. Transfer only shifts impact, it does not eliminate the activity." },
  { id:40502, domain:3, level:3, question:"Purchasing cyber insurance to cover potential breach losses is an example of which response?", options:["Risk avoidance through ceasing the data processing that creates the exposure here","Risk transfer (sharing), moving financial impact to a third party such as an insurer","Risk mitigation through deploying additional preventive technical safeguards internally","Risk acceptance by formally documenting tolerance of the residual exposure as-is"], correct:1, explanation:"Insurance shares financial impact with the insurer. Mitigation reduces risk through controls, not insurance." },
  { id:40503, domain:3, level:1, question:"A manager decides to take no action on a low-rated risk that falls within appetite. This is:", options:["Risk avoidance because the activity producing the risk has been halted entirely","Risk transfer because liability for the risk moves to another organizational unit overall","Risk acceptance, formally acknowledging the residual risk because it is within tolerance","Risk mitigation because ongoing monitoring continues to reduce exposure over time"], correct:2, explanation:"Accepting risk within appetite requires no new control. Avoidance would require stopping the activity." },
  { id:40504, domain:3, level:2, question:"Deploying multi-factor authentication to reduce account-takeover likelihood is best described as:", options:["Risk acceptance of the residual exposure that remains after the initial assessment overall","Risk transfer of the breach cost to an external managed service provider","Risk avoidance by removing all remote access from the environment completely","Risk mitigation, applying a control that lowers the likelihood of the event occurring"], correct:3, explanation:"MFA is a mitigating control reducing likelihood. Avoidance would mean removing access entirely." },
  { id:40505, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY factor in selecting a risk response should be:", options:["Alignment of residual risk with the organization's defined risk appetite and tolerance","The cost of the most advanced control solution currently available on the market","The preference of the IT department that will eventually operate the new control","The speed at which the chosen control can be technically implemented in production overall"], correct:0, explanation:"Responses are chosen to bring risk within appetite. Vendor cost alone does not drive the decision." },
  { id:40506, domain:3, level:2, question:"When the cost of a control exceeds the potential loss it prevents, the BEST response is often to:", options:["Implement the control regardless to demonstrate strong organizational due diligence overall","Accept the risk if it remains within appetite, since the control cost is not justified","Transfer the risk by purchasing the most comprehensive insurance policy available","Avoid the risk by terminating the underlying business activity entirely and at once"], correct:1, explanation:"Cost-ineffective controls are not justified; acceptance is rational when within appetite. Avoidance is excessive here." },
  { id:40507, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which response is MOST appropriate for a risk whose impact would be catastrophic and unaffordable?", options:["Acceptance, documenting the residual exposure and continuing operations entirely unchanged overall","Mitigation only through low-cost detective controls applied after the event has occurred","Avoidance of the activity, or transfer of the bulk of the financial impact to another party","Deferral of any decision until the next scheduled annual enterprise risk assessment cycle"], correct:2, explanation:"Catastrophic, unaffordable risk warrants avoidance or transfer. Accepting it would be imprudent." },
  { id:40508, domain:3, level:2, question:"Outsourcing a process to a specialized vendor with stronger controls is a form of:", options:["Risk acceptance, because the residual exposure is simply tolerated by the business as-is","Risk avoidance, because the organization stops performing all of the related work itself","Risk mitigation, achieved solely through internal control improvements within the firm","Risk transfer/sharing, since responsibility and some impact move to the chosen vendor"], correct:3, explanation:"Outsourcing shares risk with the vendor. The organization still retains accountability, so it is not pure avoidance." },
  { id:40509, domain:3, level:1, question:"A residual risk remains above appetite after mitigation. The risk owner should NEXT:", options:["Consider additional responses such as further mitigation, transfer, or avoidance options","Automatically accept the residual risk because mitigating controls were already applied overall","Remove the risk from the register because a mitigating control has now been implemented","Escalate only at the next scheduled annual board-level risk reporting checkpoint date"], correct:0, explanation:"If residual risk exceeds appetite, more response is needed. Accepting or removing it ignores the breach of appetite." },
  { id:40510, domain:3, level:2, question:"Risk appetite is BEST described as:", options:["The maximum loss the organization could theoretically suffer in a single severe event","The amount and type of risk an organization is willing to pursue or retain over time","The complete list of all controls the organization has currently implemented in total","The probability that a specific identified threat will actually materialize this year"], correct:1, explanation:"Appetite is willingness to take risk. The single-event maximum describes a different exposure concept." },
  { id:40511, domain:3, level:3, question:"When designing a new control, the FIRST consideration should be:", options:["The specific vendor product that will eventually be purchased to enforce the control","The control's color-coded status as it will appear on the executive risk dashboard","The control objective and the specific risk the control is intended to address fully","The training schedule for the staff who will eventually operate the control daily"], correct:2, explanation:"Control design starts from the objective/risk addressed. Vendor selection comes later in the process." },
  { id:40512, domain:3, level:2, question:"A control that stops an unwanted event before it occurs is classified as:", options:["Detective, because it identifies events only after they have already happened fully","Corrective, because it restores systems following a disruptive incident afterward","Compensating, because it substitutes for an absent primary control in the design","Preventive, because it acts to stop the unwanted event from occurring at all here"], correct:3, explanation:"Preventive controls act before the event. Detective controls identify events after occurrence." },
  { id:40513, domain:3, level:1, question:"Audit log review that flags unauthorized access after it happens is which control type?", options:["Detective, since it identifies the event after it has already occurred in the system","Preventive, since it blocks the unauthorized access attempt before it can complete","Directive, since it instructs staff on the correct security behavior they must follow","Deterrent, since its mere visible presence discourages potential would-be wrongdoers"], correct:0, explanation:"Log review detects events after the fact. A preventive control would block the attempt outright." },
  { id:40514, domain:3, level:3, question:"Restoring data from backups after a ransomware incident is an example of a control that is:", options:["Preventive, designed to stop the ransomware from executing in the environment initially","Corrective, designed to remediate and restore the environment after the event occurs","Detective, designed to discover the presence of the malware within the environment first","Directive, designed to mandate the acceptable use of organizational systems by staff"], correct:1, explanation:"Restoration after an event is corrective. Detective controls only discover, they do not restore." },
  { id:40515, domain:3, level:2, question:"A security awareness policy that instructs employees how to handle data is which category?", options:["Technical, because the policy is enforced automatically by the system configuration itself","Physical, because it governs access to the organization's facilities and equipment areas","Administrative, because it is a managerial or procedural directive aimed at people directly","Detective, because it identifies and reports policy violations only after they have occurred"], correct:2, explanation:"Policies are administrative controls. Technical controls are enforced by systems, not documents." },
  { id:40516, domain:3, level:3, question:"A locked server-room door and badge reader are examples of which control category?", options:["Administrative controls, because they are formally documented within a security policy overall","Technical controls, because the access logic runs entirely within software components","Corrective controls, because they restore facility access following a security breach","Physical controls, because they protect tangible facilities, equipment, and entry points"], correct:3, explanation:"Door locks and badge readers are physical controls. Administrative controls are policy/procedure based." },
  { id:40517, domain:3, level:2, question:"Encryption configured on a database is BEST categorized as which type of control?", options:["Technical (logical) control, enforced through system and software mechanisms in operation","Administrative control, since it is merely described within a governance procedure document","Physical control, since its purpose is to protect the data center hardware enclosure racks","Deterrent control, since the visible use of encryption discourages would-be attackers alone"], correct:0, explanation:"Encryption is a technical control enforced by software. It is not a policy or a physical safeguard." },
  { id:40518, domain:3, level:1, question:"A compensating control is implemented when:", options:["The primary control is fully effective and there are no remaining gaps to be addressed","A primary control is not feasible, so an alternative provides comparable risk assurance","Management chooses to accept the risk and then removes all the existing controls in place","The risk has been transferred to a third party entirely through a formal legal contract"], correct:1, explanation:"Compensating controls substitute when the primary control is infeasible. They are not used when no gap exists." },
  { id:40519, domain:3, level:3, question:"The effectiveness of a control is BEST determined by:", options:["Confirming the control was purchased from a reputable and well-known security vendor","Verifying that the control documentation exists and is properly signed by management","Testing whether the control actually operates as intended to mitigate the targeted risk","Counting the total number of staff members who attended the control awareness training overall"], correct:2, explanation:"Effectiveness is proven by testing operation against intent. Documentation alone does not prove it works." },
  { id:40520, domain:3, level:2, question:"Defense in depth refers to:", options:["Relying on a single strong perimeter control to protect all of the internal assets fully","Transferring all of the organization's technical risk to a managed security service provider","Accepting the residual risk entirely once a perimeter firewall has been properly deployed","Layering multiple controls so that the failure of any one does not expose the asset directly"], correct:3, explanation:"Defense in depth layers controls. Relying on one perimeter control is the opposite approach." },
  { id:40521, domain:3, level:2, question:"The control owner is PRIMARILY responsible for:", options:["Ensuring the assigned control is designed, operating, and remains effective over time fully","Approving the organization's overall enterprise risk appetite statement for the year ahead","Setting the entire annual budget for the organization's information security program in full","Independently auditing the control to provide objective third-line assurance to the board"], correct:0, explanation:"Control owners ensure their control operates effectively. Independent audit is a separate, third-line role." },
  { id:40522, domain:3, level:3, question:"Accountability for a risk response decision ultimately rests with:", options:["The internal audit function that independently tests the related controls for effectiveness","The risk owner who owns the asset or process and accepts the resulting residual risk","The control operator who performs the routine day-to-day control activity as assigned","The external regulator that oversees the organization's particular industry sector closely"], correct:1, explanation:"The risk owner is accountable for the response and residual risk. Audit only provides assurance." },
  { id:40523, domain:3, level:1, question:"Separation of the control owner from the control tester is important because it:", options:["Reduces the overall cost of operating the control on a recurring basis across the year","Speeds up the implementation timeline for new control deployments across the enterprise","Preserves objectivity and independence when evaluating the control's true effectiveness","Allows the control owner to directly approve their own control testing results each cycle"], correct:2, explanation:"Independence preserves objective testing. Letting owners assess their own controls undermines assurance." },
  { id:40524, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a control spans multiple departments, the BEST practice is to:", options:["Leave ownership undefined so that each team can contribute informally whenever needed overall","Rotate ownership of the control monthly among all of the departments that touch it","Transfer the control entirely to the internal audit department for them to manage it","Assign clear, single-point accountability for the control to one named responsible owner"], correct:3, explanation:"Clear single-point accountability prevents gaps. Undefined ownership leads to controls being neglected." },
  { id:40525, domain:3, level:3, question:"The MOST effective way to address risk from a critical third-party service provider is to:", options:["Include right-to-audit and security requirements within the binding contractual agreement","Assume the provider's controls are adequate simply because they are a large known vendor","Avoid documenting the relationship at all in order to reduce the administrative overhead","Rely exclusively on the provider's own marketing claims about its security posture and tools"], correct:0, explanation:"Contractual security and audit rights give enforceable assurance. Assuming adequacy provides none." },
  { id:40526, domain:3, level:2, question:"A SOC 2 Type II report from a vendor PRIMARILY provides assurance about:", options:["The vendor's future financial solvency and viability over the next several fiscal years","The operating effectiveness of the vendor's controls measured over a period of time","The organization's own internal controls relating specifically to that particular vendor","The market reputation of the vendor among its various industry peers and competitors"], correct:1, explanation:"A Type II report covers control operating effectiveness over a period. It does not assess financial solvency." },
  { id:40527, domain:3, level:3, question:"When a vendor cannot meet a security requirement, the organization should FIRST:", options:["Immediately terminate the contract without first evaluating any other available alternatives","Ignore the identified gap entirely because the vendor is already contractually engaged now","Assess the residual risk and consider compensating controls or a formal risk acceptance","Transfer the vendor's entire risk to a comprehensive cyber insurance policy all at once"], correct:2, explanation:"Assess residual risk and consider compensating controls. Immediate termination skips evaluating viable options." },
  { id:40528, domain:3, level:2, question:"Concentration risk from third parties refers to:", options:["The risk that a single vendor stores too much encrypted data within one physical location","The risk that all of the contract terms are concentrated within a single legal clause text","The geographic clustering of the organization's own internal data centers in one region","Over-reliance on a single provider whose failure would have wide and significant impact"], correct:3, explanation:"Concentration risk is over-reliance on one provider. The other options describe unrelated concepts." },
  { id:40529, domain:3, level:1, question:"Fourth-party risk in a supply chain refers to risk arising from:", options:["The subcontractors and downstream suppliers that the organization's own vendor relies upon","The organization's own employees who routinely interact with the primary contracted vendor","The regulators who oversee the organization's various third-party relationships and contracts","The organization's own customers who ultimately consume the vendor-delivered service output"], correct:0, explanation:"Fourth-party risk comes from a vendor's own suppliers. The organization's employees are an internal matter." },
  { id:40530, domain:3, level:2, question:"A formal risk acceptance (exception) should ALWAYS include:", options:["An open-ended approval with no expiration date so that it never needs to be revisited again","An expiration date together with a named approver who holds the appropriate authority level","Approval granted by the control operator who personally implements the affected control daily","Removal of the underlying risk from the register once the exception has been formally signed"], correct:1, explanation:"Exceptions need an expiry and an authorized approver. Open-ended acceptances escape periodic review." },
  { id:40531, domain:3, level:3, question:"Who should approve a risk acceptance that exceeds a business unit's authority?", options:["The control operator who performs the affected daily control activity within the business unit","An internal auditor who is currently reviewing the unit's overall control environment closely","Senior management or the governing body that holds authority for that particular risk level","Any available manager regardless of their formally delegated risk acceptance authority level"], correct:2, explanation:"Acceptances must be approved at the proper authority level. Operators and auditors lack that authority." },
  { id:40532, domain:3, level:2, question:"Risk acceptances should be reviewed periodically because:", options:["Controls never change at all once they have been initially implemented in the environment","Auditors require that every single acceptance be permanently retained completely unchanged","An acceptance automatically converts itself into avoidance after exactly twelve months pass","The conditions, threats, and impact underlying the original acceptance can change over time"], correct:3, explanation:"Underlying conditions change, so acceptances need review. They do not auto-convert to avoidance." },
  { id:40533, domain:3, level:1, question:"A growing backlog of unaddressed control exceptions MOST likely indicates:", options:["Weakness in remediation discipline and the potential accumulation of unmanaged risk over time","An exceptionally mature and well-controlled risk environment across the whole organization","That the organization's risk appetite has simply been set far too conservatively and too low","That the internal audit function is currently testing the organization's controls too frequently"], correct:0, explanation:"A rising exception backlog signals weak remediation and accumulating risk, not a mature environment." },
  { id:40534, domain:3, level:3, question:"A key risk indicator (KRI) is MOST useful when it:", options:["Reports historical losses only after major risk incidents have already concluded entirely","Provides an early warning signal that the organization's risk exposure is actively changing","Measures the total annual budget that has been allocated to the security program this year overall","Counts only the number of employees who have completed mandatory compliance training"], correct:1, explanation:"KRIs give early warning of changing exposure. Pure historical loss reporting is lagging, not predictive." },
  { id:40535, domain:3, level:2, question:"The PRIMARY difference between a KRI and a KPI is that a KRI:", options:["Measures the past financial performance of a completed and closed-out business project only","Is always expressed as a percentage value, while a KPI is always expressed as a raw count","Signals changes in risk exposure, while a KPI measures the achievement of performance goals","Is reported only to internal auditors, while a KPI is reported only to external customers"], correct:2, explanation:"KRIs track risk exposure; KPIs track performance. Format and audience are not the distinguishing factor." },
  { id:40536, domain:3, level:3, question:"A key control indicator (KCI) MOST directly measures:", options:["The total financial return delivered by a recently completed major business initiative effort","The organization's overall current market share within its competitive industry sector now","The total number of individual risks currently recorded in the enterprise risk register file","Whether a specific control is operating effectively as it was originally designed to operate"], correct:3, explanation:"KCIs measure control effectiveness. Market share and register counts are unrelated to control operation." },
  { id:40537, domain:3, level:2, question:"An effective KRI threshold should be:", options:["Linked to the organization's risk appetite and tolerance so breaches prompt timely action","Set arbitrarily high so that the indicator essentially never triggers any alert at all in use","Identical across every single organization regardless of its specific context or risk appetite","Defined only after a major incident has already caused a material loss to the organization"], correct:0, explanation:"Thresholds should tie to appetite so breaches drive action. Arbitrarily high thresholds defeat early warning." },
  { id:40538, domain:3, level:1, question:"A leading indicator differs from a lagging indicator in that it:", options:["Reports the relevant outcomes only after a risk event has already fully materialized in scope","Predicts potential future changes in risk before the associated events actually occur in time","Can only be derived from the completed and audited financial statements of the organization","Is always inherently less reliable than any corresponding available lagging risk indicator"], correct:1, explanation:"Leading indicators predict; lagging indicators report after the fact. Leading ones are not inherently less reliable." },
  { id:40539, domain:3, level:3, question:"Continuous control monitoring provides the GREATEST benefit by:", options:["Replacing the need for any form of independent assurance or internal audit activity entirely overall","Eliminating the requirement to ever update the enterprise risk register in the future at all","Identifying control failures closer to real time so that emerging issues are caught much sooner","Guaranteeing that no control within the environment will ever fail again in the future fully"], correct:2, explanation:"Continuous monitoring shortens detection time. It supplements, but does not replace, independent assurance." },
  { id:40540, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which is the BEST example of a KRI for unauthorized access risk?", options:["The total current annual headcount of the organization's information security department staff","The number of new laptops purchased by the organization during this particular fiscal quarter","The percentage of the overall IT budget that has been allocated to networking hardware spend","The trend in the number of failed and anomalous login attempts observed over a period of time"], correct:3, explanation:"Failed/anomalous login trends signal access risk. Headcount and hardware spend are not risk indicators." },
  { id:40541, domain:3, level:2, question:"KRIs should be reviewed and updated periodically because:", options:["The risk landscape and business context evolve, which changes what is genuinely predictive","Indicators that worked effectively once will always remain relevant indefinitely without review","Regulators strictly forbid the continued use of any single indicator for more than one year","Updating KRIs is the required mechanism for resetting the organization's overall risk appetite"], correct:0, explanation:"KRIs must evolve with the risk landscape. Updating them does not reset appetite, which is governance-set." },
  { id:40542, domain:3, level:3, question:"Control testing PRIMARILY aims to determine whether controls are:", options:["Documented in a formal policy that has been reviewed and approved by the board of directors","Both designed appropriately and operating effectively in actual day-to-day practice over time","The least expensive available option among all of the comparable control solutions on offer","Owned by a manager who holds a sufficiently senior and high-ranking organizational job title overall"], correct:1, explanation:"Testing evaluates design and operating effectiveness. A title or low cost does not establish effectiveness." },
  { id:40543, domain:3, level:1, question:"A control that is well designed but not consistently performed is described as having:", options:["A design deficiency despite the control being operated consistently and reliably in practice","No deficiency at all whatsoever because the design of the control on paper is fundamentally sound","An operating effectiveness deficiency despite the control having an otherwise adequate design","A fully transferred risk that as a result no longer requires any ongoing monitoring at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Inconsistent performance is an operating effectiveness gap. The design itself is not the deficiency here." },
  { id:40544, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST evidence that a control is operating effectively is:", options:["A vendor brochure that describes the control product's various marketed features and benefits","A verbal assurance provided by the control owner stating that the control generally works well","The simple fact that no related incident has been formally reported at all during this past year overall","Direct testing of the control's actual operation over a representative period of time in practice"], correct:3, explanation:"Direct testing over time is strongest. Absence of reported incidents may simply mean detection is failing." },
  { id:40545, domain:3, level:3, question:"Sampling is used in control testing PRIMARILY to:", options:["Draw a supportable conclusion about a whole population of items efficiently and economically","Guarantee that every single individual instance of the control is examined separately each time","Deliberately avoid testing any transactions that might happen to reveal a real control failure","Replace the requirement to first clearly define the control objective before any testing begins"], correct:0, explanation:"Sampling lets testers conclude about a population efficiently. It is not meant to avoid finding failures." },
  { id:40546, domain:3, level:2, question:"A control self-assessment (CSA) is BEST characterized as:", options:["An independent audit that is performed solely by the organization's external audit firm staff overall","Process owners themselves evaluating the design and effectiveness of their own assigned controls","An automated penetration test that is executed directly against the live production systems","A formal regulatory examination conducted by an external supervisory or oversight body alone"], correct:1, explanation:"CSA has process owners assess their own controls. It is participative, not an independent external audit." },
  { id:40547, domain:3, level:3, question:"If control testing reveals a deficiency, the risk practitioner should FIRST:", options:["Immediately remove the related risk entry entirely from the enterprise risk register at once","Conclude that the entire control environment is irreparable and then halt all operations fully","Assess the impact of the identified deficiency on residual risk and then report it appropriately","Reassign the deficient control to the internal audit department for them to operate it going forward"], correct:2, explanation:"Assess impact on residual risk and report it. Removing the risk or halting operations is not warranted." },
  { id:40548, domain:3, level:2, question:"Risk reporting to senior management should PRIMARILY:", options:["Include every single technical log entry that was generated by systems during the period","Focus only on the specific controls that successfully passed their most recent round of testing","Avoid mentioning any residual risk whatsoever in order to prevent unnecessarily alarming the board","Present risk in clear business terms that enable informed and timely decision making by leaders"], correct:3, explanation:"Reports should enable decisions in business terms. Hiding residual risk defeats the purpose of reporting." },
  { id:40549, domain:3, level:1, question:"The MOST important quality of effective risk reporting is that it is:", options:["Accurate, timely, and relevant to the specific needs of the intended audience receiving the report","Lengthy and exhaustive in detail in order to demonstrate the genuine depth of the analysis done","Written entirely in highly technical and specialized language in order to convey real precision","Distributed as infrequently as is reasonably possible so as to reduce the overall reporting overhead"], correct:0, explanation:"Accurate, timely, relevant reporting drives action. Length and jargon hinder, rather than help, decisions." },
  { id:40550, domain:3, level:2, question:"Risk reports should be tailored to the audience because:", options:["All stakeholders fundamentally require an identical level of detail regardless of their actual role","Different stakeholders need different levels of detail and context in order to act appropriately","Tailoring reports is a strict regulatory requirement that is enforced in every single jurisdiction","Executives genuinely prefer the same raw underlying data that the engineers analyze every day"], correct:1, explanation:"Audiences need different detail to act. A single technical format does not serve executives and engineers alike." },
  { id:40551, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk dashboard using a heat map PRIMARILY helps stakeholders to:", options:["Calculate the exact precise monetary value of every individual risk in the register precisely","Completely replace the underlying detailed risk register entirely with a single colorful graphic","Quickly visualize and prioritize the organization's risks by their likelihood and their impact","Eliminate the ongoing need for any narrative explanation of the various risks that are shown"], correct:2, explanation:"Heat maps aid quick prioritization. They summarize, but do not replace, the detailed register or narrative." },
  { id:40552, domain:3, level:1, question:"When reporting a newly identified critical risk, the practitioner should:", options:["Wait until the next scheduled annual report in order to avoid disrupting the routine reporting cycle","Resolve the critical risk entirely on their own without informing any other stakeholders at all","Record the risk quietly in the register without any form of escalation to management whatsoever","Escalate the risk promptly to the appropriate stakeholders so that timely decisions can be made"], correct:3, explanation:"Critical risks warrant prompt escalation. Delaying to the annual cycle could allow harm to occur." },
  { id:40553, domain:3, level:2, question:"Aggregating related individual risks for reporting is valuable because it:", options:["Reveals the combined overall exposure that the individual register entries may understate alone","Hides material exposures from the view of senior management in order to simplify the final report","Permanently removes the underlying detailed individual entries from all of the organization's records","Eliminates the ongoing need to assign any accountable owner to the resulting aggregated risks"], correct:0, explanation:"Aggregation reveals combined exposure. It should not hide detail or remove ownership of underlying risks." },
  { id:40554, domain:3, level:3, question:"The risk register PRIMARILY serves to:", options:["Store only those controls that have already failed their most recent effectiveness testing cycle overall","Provide a centralized record of identified risks together with their treatment and current status","Completely replace the organization's incident response runbook and procedure documentation set","List the full names of every single employee currently in the information security team roster"], correct:1, explanation:"The register centralizes identified risks and their treatment. It is not a staff roster or incident runbook." },
  { id:40555, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which element is MOST essential in a risk register entry?", options:["The full marketing brand name of the particular vendor that sold a related security product","The personal mobile telephone number of the individual analyst who reported the risk first","A clearly named risk owner who is accountable for the risk and its corresponding response","The exact verbatim wording of every related corporate press release issued about the risk"], correct:2, explanation:"A named owner is essential for accountability. Vendor names and press wording are not core register fields." },
  { id:40556, domain:3, level:3, question:"The risk register should be updated:", options:["Only one single time, at the precise moment when the register is first initially created","Only at those times when an external auditor specifically requests a full refresh of the data","Exclusively at the conclusion of the organization's full multi-year strategic planning cycle","Continuously and on an ongoing basis as risks, controls, and conditions change over time"], correct:3, explanation:"Registers must be kept current as conditions change. A one-time update quickly becomes outdated." },
  { id:40557, domain:3, level:2, question:"Stale, outdated entries in a risk register MOST directly lead to:", options:["Decisions that are based on inaccurate exposure data, which in turn undermines the responses","More accurate and far more reliable risk-based decision making across the whole organization","The automatic and timely remediation of all of the various risks that were originally recorded","A measurable reduction in the organization's overall current residual risk exposure level"], correct:0, explanation:"Stale entries mislead decisions. They do not auto-remediate risk or improve decision accuracy." },
  { id:40558, domain:3, level:1, question:"A risk treatment plan should clearly define:", options:["Only the high-level overall intention, while leaving the owners and the due dates unspecified","The specific actions, the responsible owners, the timelines, and the expected residual risk","Solely the total budget figure with no associated tasks, owners, or accountability defined at all","The external marketing strategy for promoting the security program to the outside world"], correct:1, explanation:"Treatment plans specify actions, owners, dates, and target residual risk. Vague intentions are insufficient." },
  { id:40559, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY purpose of a risk treatment plan is to:", options:["Document who exactly to blame after a particular risk event has already occurred in practice","Permanently transfer all accountability for the underlying risk to the internal audit function","Bring an identified risk to within acceptable levels through deliberately planned action steps","Catalog and store historical incidents purely for the organization's long-term archive records"], correct:2, explanation:"Treatment plans drive risk to acceptable levels via planned action. They are not blame or archival tools." },
  { id:40560, domain:3, level:2, question:"Progress against risk treatment plans should be monitored to:", options:["Replace the future need to ever test the resulting implemented controls for their effectiveness","Allow the original risk entry to be deleted entirely before any of the planned action is taken","Demonstrate that ongoing monitoring of the organization's risk is no longer necessary at all","Ensure that remediation actions are actually completed and that they remain on their schedule"], correct:3, explanation:"Monitoring confirms remediation stays on track. It does not replace later control testing or end monitoring." },
  { id:40561, domain:3, level:2, question:"When remediation will take significant time, an interim measure is often to:", options:["Apply a compensating control in order to reduce the overall exposure during the interim period","Ignore the underlying risk completely until the full planned remediation has been finished entirely","Immediately close out the risk simply because a documented treatment plan already exists on paper","Transfer accountability for the remediation delay directly to the organization's internal audit team"], correct:0, explanation:"Compensating controls reduce exposure during long remediation. Ignoring the risk leaves it unmanaged." },
  { id:40562, domain:3, level:3, question:"The organization's risk profile is BEST described as:", options:["A single financial figure that represents the organization's total annual security program spend","A snapshot of the organization's overall risk exposure measured at a particular point in time","The complete list of all of the vendors that are currently under an active contractual agreement","The full roster of all personnel who are currently assigned to the enterprise risk committee"], correct:1, explanation:"The risk profile is a snapshot of overall exposure. It is neither a spend figure nor a vendor list." },
  { id:40563, domain:3, level:1, question:"Maintaining an accurate risk profile requires:", options:["A single one-time assessment that is performed once at the organization's original founding date","Deliberately excluding any newly emerging risks until at least the next decade's scheduled review","Ongoing updates that reflect changes in the threats, the controls, and the underlying business","Removing from the profile all of the risks that have any mitigating control applied to them at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Profiles need continuous updating. A one-time assessment cannot reflect an evolving threat landscape." },
  { id:40564, domain:3, level:2, question:"A significant change in the business, such as a merger, should trigger:", options:["No change at all, because the existing current risk profile already adequately covers everything","The immediate deletion of the entire prior risk register without any replacement being prepared","The transfer of all of the newly introduced risks directly to the firm that was just acquired","A full reassessment in order to update the organization's risk profile for the new exposures"], correct:3, explanation:"Major change warrants reassessment of the profile. Assuming the old profile still holds is unsafe." },
  { id:40565, domain:3, level:3, question:"The risk profile is MOST useful to senior management when it:", options:["Summarizes the key exposures against appetite in order to support strategic decision making","Lists exhaustive low-level technical detail about every individual server configuration in scope","Reports only those risks that have already been completely and finally remediated and closed","Deliberately omits all residual risk so that the overall risk picture appears more favorable"], correct:0, explanation:"Profiles summarize exposure against appetite for decisions. Omitting residual risk distorts the picture." },
  { id:40566, domain:3, level:2, question:"Residual risk is BEST defined as the risk that remains:", options:["Before any of the relevant controls or risk responses have yet been applied to the exposure","After the chosen risk responses and the related controls have been applied to inherent risk","Only within the organization's various third-party relationships outside its own boundary","Exclusively within those risks that have already been formally accepted by senior management"], correct:1, explanation:"Residual risk remains after responses are applied. Risk before any control is inherent risk." },
  { id:40567, domain:3, level:3, question:"Inherent risk refers to the level of risk:", options:["Remaining after all of the relevant mitigating controls are fully designed and operating well","That has already been formally transferred to an external insurance provider via a contract","Existing before any controls or mitigating actions are considered or applied to the exposure","That applies only to those deliberately accepted low-priority exposures within the appetite"], correct:2, explanation:"Inherent risk is pre-control. The level remaining after controls is residual risk." },
  { id:40568, domain:3, level:2, question:"A directive control is one that:", options:["Automatically reverses any unauthorized changes that are made to a system configuration baseline","Detects anomalies present within the system logs after a particular event has already occurred","Physically prevents unauthorized entry into a restricted and sensitive facility area or room","Mandates or encourages a desired behavior, such as a documented policy requirement for staff"], correct:3, explanation:"Directive controls mandate behavior. Reversing changes is corrective; detecting anomalies is detective." },
  { id:40569, domain:3, level:1, question:"A deterrent control reduces risk PRIMARILY by:", options:["Discouraging potential would-be wrongdoers through its visible presence or a clear consequence","Restoring all of the affected systems back to a known-good state following a security incident","Encrypting all of the sensitive data so that it simply cannot be read at all if it is ever stolen","Automatically generating an alert whenever a particular policy violation is actively detected"], correct:0, explanation:"Deterrents discourage by visible presence. Restoration is corrective and encryption is preventive/technical." },
  { id:40570, domain:3, level:2, question:"When selecting between two effective controls, cost-benefit analysis helps to:", options:["Always select the single most expensive control available in order to maximize protection levels","Choose the option that delivers adequate risk reduction at a reasonable and justifiable cost","Eliminate the need to consider the organization's risk appetite at all during the selection process","Guarantee that the chosen control will never require any form of future testing once deployed"], correct:1, explanation:"Cost-benefit picks adequate reduction at justifiable cost. The most expensive option is not automatically best." },
  { id:40571, domain:3, level:3, question:"The BEST time to identify needed controls is:", options:["After a significant incident has already occurred and caused substantial damage to the business","Only when an external auditor specifically flags a missing control during their fieldwork visit","During the design of a process or system, by building the security in from the very beginning","At the very end of a project, just immediately before the system is formally decommissioned"], correct:2, explanation:"Building controls in during design is most effective. Waiting for an incident or audit is reactive." },
  { id:40572, domain:3, level:1, question:"A control gap is BEST described as:", options:["A surplus of multiple overlapping controls that all happen to address the same single risk fully","The natural and expected delay between a control's initial design and its first annual testing cycle","An exception to a control that has already been formally approved by the organization's leadership","A difference between the control that is actually needed and the control that is currently in place"], correct:3, explanation:"A gap is the shortfall between needed and existing control. Overlap is redundancy, not a gap." },
  { id:40573, domain:3, level:2, question:"The risk practitioner's role in risk response is PRIMARILY to:", options:["Facilitate and advise on the available options while the risk owners actually make the decisions","Personally make the final acceptance decision for every single enterprise-level risk on the register","Directly operate all of the various technical controls deployed across the entire organization","Replace senior management entirely in the task of setting the organization's overall risk appetite"], correct:0, explanation:"Practitioners facilitate and advise; risk owners decide. Practitioners do not set appetite or own decisions." },
  { id:40574, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which BEST reflects effective integration of risk response into operations?", options:["Risk responses are tracked entirely separately and are never linked to any daily business processes","Risk treatment actions are embedded directly into the operational plans and the daily workflows","Responses are documented one single time and then are never revisited again after the initial sign-off","Only the central risk team is ever made aware of the agreed response actions and their assigned owners"], correct:1, explanation:"Embedding responses into operations drives execution. Isolated, one-time documentation rarely gets implemented." },
  { id:40575, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MAIN reason to validate a control after implementation is to confirm it:", options:["Was indeed purchased within the boundaries of the approved capital expenditure budget line item","Has been given a sufficiently descriptive and memorable internal name in the control catalog list","Actually reduces the specifically targeted risk as intended under real operating conditions in use","Was deployed considerably faster than the original project implementation schedule had planned for"], correct:2, explanation:"Validation confirms the control reduces the targeted risk. Budget and naming do not establish effectiveness." },
  { id:40576, domain:3, level:3, question:"Over-controlling a low risk is undesirable because it:", options:["Always meaningfully strengthens the overall business case for the broader security program funding","Automatically eliminates all of the residual risk from the organization's operating environment fully","Is explicitly required by virtually every recognized information security and risk control framework","Wastes finite resources that could otherwise be applied to address the higher-priority exposures"], correct:3, explanation:"Over-controlling low risk wastes resources better spent elsewhere. It is not mandated by frameworks." },
  { id:40577, domain:3, level:2, question:"A trend of increasing KRI values approaching its threshold should prompt:", options:["Proactive investigation along with a possible response action before any actual breach can occur","Ignoring the observed trend entirely until the defined threshold is actually formally breached first","The immediate deletion of the relevant KRI in order to avoid triggering any future false alarms","Raising the threshold value so that the indicator simply no longer appears at all concerning to view"], correct:0, explanation:"A rising trend warrants proactive action. Raising the threshold to hide it defeats the indicator's purpose." },
  { id:40578, domain:3, level:1, question:"The BEST source for determining whether residual risk is acceptable is the:", options:["Personal informal opinion of whichever individual risk analyst happens to be available at the moment","Organization's formally documented risk appetite and its associated defined tolerance levels","Marketing materials provided by the security control vendor that is currently under consideration","Average residual risk that has been reported by various unrelated peer organizations in the sector"], correct:1, explanation:"Acceptability is judged against documented appetite and tolerance, not individual opinion or peer averages." },
  { id:40579, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk owner disagrees with a recommended response. The practitioner should:", options:["Override the risk owner entirely and then implement the recommended response unilaterally at once overall","Drop the risk entirely from the register simply because the owner declined the offered advice","Document the rationale, ensure an informed decision is made, and escalate the matter if it is needed","Report the disagreeing owner directly to the external regulators for refusing the recommendation"], correct:2, explanation:"The practitioner documents and escalates as needed; the owner decides. Unilateral override is inappropriate." },
  { id:40580, domain:3, level:2, question:"Mapping controls to the risks they address helps the organization to:", options:["Definitively prove that no risk will ever actually materialize again in the future environment at all","Eliminate entirely the need to assign clear accountable ownership to any individual control in scope","Completely replace the enterprise risk register with a single static and unchanging control inventory","Identify any coverage gaps and avoid maintaining redundant or unnecessarily duplicated controls"], correct:3, explanation:"Control-to-risk mapping reveals gaps and redundancy. It does not guarantee zero future events." },
  { id:40581, domain:3, level:2, question:"The frequency of control testing should PRIMARILY be based on:", options:["The criticality of the particular control along with the level of the risk that the control addresses","The personal preference and convenience of whichever individual happens to be performing the testing","Testing every single control with an identical fixed frequency regardless of its associated risk level","Whichever testing schedule happens to minimize the total annual control testing effort overall best"], correct:0, explanation:"Testing frequency is risk-based, driven by control criticality. Uniform frequency ignores differing risk." },
  { id:40582, domain:3, level:3, question:"An automated control is generally PREFERRED over a manual one because it:", options:["Completely eliminates the need for any form of human oversight or ongoing monitoring whatsoever","Operates consistently and is therefore considerably less prone to human error or simple omission","Is always inherently cheaper to design and implement than any equivalent manual control alternative","Can simply never fail or be misconfigured in any way at all once it has been deployed into production"], correct:1, explanation:"Automation gives consistency and fewer human errors. It can still fail or be misconfigured, so oversight remains." },
  { id:40583, domain:3, level:1, question:"The PRIMARY benefit of linking KPIs to KRIs is to:", options:["Completely replace all qualitative risk analysis with purely numeric and quantitative measures only","Guarantee that every single project will reliably achieve its originally scheduled completion date","Connect performance shortfalls to the potential corresponding increases in the firm's risk exposure","Remove the future need to ever formally report any risk information to senior management again"], correct:2, explanation:"Linking KPIs to KRIs connects performance gaps to rising risk. It does not eliminate risk reporting." },
  { id:40584, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a transferred risk materializes, the organization typically retains:", options:["No responsibility at all whatsoever, since the entire risk was already fully transferred away before","Only the upside benefit of the activity while the third party absorbs every single possible loss","An obligation to immediately and completely avoid the underlying activity entirely from that point","Residual accountability along with any of the actual impact that is not covered by the transfer"], correct:3, explanation:"Transfer leaves residual accountability and uncovered impact with the organization. Transfer is never total." },
  { id:40585, domain:3, level:3, question:"The MOST appropriate response to a risk with low impact and low likelihood is usually:", options:["Acceptance of the risk, provided that the risk genuinely remains within the defined risk appetite","Investing immediately in the single most advanced available mitigating technology on the market","Avoidance of the risk by completely discontinuing the entire related business activity right away","Transfer of the risk through a comprehensive and relatively costly external insurance policy now"], correct:0, explanation:"Low/low risk within appetite is typically accepted. Heavy mitigation or avoidance would be disproportionate." },
  { id:40586, domain:3, level:2, question:"Documenting the residual risk after each response is important because it:", options:["Definitively proves that the inherent risk has now been completely and permanently removed in full","Informs whether any further action is needed and supports a properly informed acceptance decision","Completely replaces the future requirement to ever test the implemented controls for effectiveness","Allows the risk practitioner to immediately delete the entry from the risk register at once afterward"], correct:1, explanation:"Documented residual risk drives further-action decisions. Responses rarely remove inherent risk entirely." },
  { id:40587, domain:3, level:3, question:"A 'risk owner' and a 'control owner' may differ because:", options:["The two distinct roles are legally and contractually required to always be the exact same person","Control owners always outrank the corresponding risk owners on the formal organizational chart structure","One is accountable for the overall risk while the other ensures that a specific control operates well","Risk owners only ever exist within the context of third-party relationships, and never internally at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Risk owners own the risk; control owners ensure controls operate. They need not be the same individual." },
  { id:40588, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to ensure risk responses remain effective over time is to:", options:["Implement each response one single time and then simply assume it will remain effective forever after","Transfer every single response to an external third party in order to avoid any internal effort at all","Remove the responses from the risk register as soon as they have been initially implemented in full","Continuously monitor the controls and reassess the resulting residual risk on a periodic basis"], correct:3, explanation:"Ongoing monitoring and reassessment sustain effectiveness. One-time implementation cannot account for change." },
  { id:40589, domain:3, level:1, question:"Quantitative risk reporting (e.g., in monetary terms) is valuable because it:", options:["Enables clearer prioritization and a cost-benefit comparison expressed in meaningful business terms","Completely removes all of the inherent uncertainty from every single risk estimate that is produced","Is always demonstrably more accurate in every case than any corresponding qualitative assessment","Eliminates entirely the need for any form of management judgment in any related decision making"], correct:0, explanation:"Quantitative reporting aids prioritization in business terms. It does not remove uncertainty or judgment." },
  { id:40590, domain:3, level:2, question:"A risk that has materialized into an actual event (an issue) should be:", options:["Left entirely unchanged within the risk register as a purely hypothetical future possibility only","Managed through the incident or issue response process while the relevant risk record is updated","Immediately and formally accepted without any response at all simply because it has already occurred","Ignored completely because the discipline of risk management only ever concerns hypothetical events"], correct:1, explanation:"Materialized risks become issues requiring response while the risk record is updated. They are not ignored." },
  { id:40591, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY reason to communicate risk to operational staff is to:", options:["Assign clear personal blame in advance for any potential future control failures that might occur","Satisfy a formal requirement to maximize the total volume of internal company email traffic overall","Build genuine awareness so that staff support and then correctly execute the agreed risk responses","Completely replace the formal documented risk register with informal verbal status updates only"], correct:2, explanation:"Communicating risk builds the awareness needed to execute responses. It is not about assigning blame." },
  { id:40592, domain:3, level:2, question:"When two controls overlap significantly, the organization should consider:", options:["Always retaining both of the controls in place regardless of the additional cost or the redundancy","Immediately removing both of the controls altogether in order to simplify the overall environment","Transferring both of the overlapping controls to an entirely unrelated third-party service provider","Whether the observed redundancy is genuinely justified or whether one control can be streamlined"], correct:3, explanation:"Evaluate whether overlap is justified or can be streamlined. Blindly keeping or removing both is not optimal." },
  { id:40593, domain:3, level:1, question:"A control's 'design effectiveness' refers to whether the control:", options:["Would successfully achieve its stated objective if it operated exactly as it was originally intended","Is currently being performed consistently by the relevant staff in the actual day-to-day operations overall","Was indeed the single cheapest available option among all of the various considered alternatives","Has been given a clearly worded and easily memorable name within the organization's control catalog"], correct:0, explanation:"Design effectiveness asks if the control would work as intended. Whether it is performed is operating effectiveness." },
  { id:40594, domain:3, level:3, question:"The risk practitioner should report KRI breaches to management because:", options:["Management genuinely enjoys receiving as much raw underlying technical data as is possible regularly","Such breaches signal exposure changes that may in turn require corresponding management decisions","Reporting the breaches will automatically and immediately resolve the underlying risk by itself fully","It transfers the full accountability for the underlying risk directly onto the reporting risk analyst"], correct:1, explanation:"KRI breaches signal exposure changes needing decisions. Reporting does not resolve the risk by itself." },
  { id:40595, domain:3, level:2, question:"Tolerance, as distinct from appetite, is BEST understood as:", options:["Exactly the same underlying concept as appetite, with no meaningful or practical difference at all","The total annual budget that the organization currently spends on its overall risk program activities","The acceptable degree of variation around the appetite before corrective action becomes required","A formal list of all of the risks that the organization has firmly decided to fully and entirely avoid"], correct:2, explanation:"Tolerance is the acceptable variation around appetite. It is related to, but distinct from, appetite itself." },
  { id:40596, domain:3, level:3, question:"A poorly defined control objective MOST likely results in:", options:["A control that nonetheless perfectly addresses its intended targeted risk every single time in use","The automatic and immediate acceptance of the underlying risk by senior management all at once","A guaranteed and measurable reduction in the total ongoing cost of operating the control over time","A control that may not actually effectively mitigate the specific risk it was intended to address"], correct:3, explanation:"Without a clear objective, the control may miss the risk. A vague objective does not improve mitigation." },
  { id:40597, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MOST effective risk reports drive action by including:", options:["Clear recommendations along with the specific decisions that are actually needed from the audience","Only the positive results and good news so that the receiving management remains fully reassured","An exhaustive and lengthy technical appendix with no accompanying executive summary at all included","Raw unprocessed data dumps that the individual reader must then fully interpret entirely on their own"], correct:0, explanation:"Reports drive action with clear recommendations. Showing only positives or raw data hinders decisions." },
  { id:40598, domain:3, level:1, question:"When residual risk is below appetite, the organization is generally:", options:["Required immediately to add even more controls in order to reduce the residual risk still further","In an acceptable risk position, although ongoing monitoring of the risk should still continue regardless","Obligated to entirely avoid the underlying business activity in order to remain fully compliant overall overall","Completely unable to report any of its risk information to senior management at all going forward"], correct:1, explanation:"Below-appetite residual risk is acceptable, but monitoring continues. Adding more control is not required." },
  { id:40599, domain:3, level:3, question:"A key reason to assign timelines to risk treatment actions is to:", options:["Allow the various planned actions to be deferred indefinitely without any consequence whatsoever","Guarantee that the underlying risk completely disappears the very moment the timeline is first set","Create clear accountability and enable the meaningful tracking of remediation progress over time","Remove entirely the need to identify any single responsible owner for the planned treatment action"], correct:2, explanation:"Timelines create accountability and enable tracking. They do not, by themselves, remove the risk." },
  { id:40600, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which scenario BEST illustrates risk sharing rather than full transfer?", options:["Buying an insurance policy that pays out the entire full value of any conceivable possible loss at all","Discontinuing a product line entirely in order to fully eliminate its associated underlying risk exposure","Accepting a particular residual risk simply because that risk falls comfortably within the appetite","A joint venture in which the various partners each bear a portion of a single shared exposure together"], correct:3, explanation:"A joint venture spreads risk among partners (sharing). Full-payout insurance is closer to complete transfer." },
  { id:40601, domain:3, level:2, question:"The risk practitioner notices a control owner has left the company. The FIRST step is to:", options:["Reassign the control ownership promptly to another suitably qualified and available individual person","Simply assume that the control will continue operating effectively without any owner indefinitely","Delete the affected control entirely from the register simply because its prior owner has departed overall","Transfer the affected control directly to the internal audit department to operate it permanently"], correct:0, explanation:"Ownership must be reassigned promptly to maintain accountability. An ownerless control risks being neglected." },
  { id:40602, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY value of integrating risk reporting with corporate governance is to:", options:["Increase the total overall number of separate committees that review the exact same underlying data","Ensure that the risk information actually reaches the decision makers and properly informs strategy","Completely replace the board's strategic oversight role with detailed operational risk reporting instead","Guarantee that the organization will simply never experience any form of loss event again in future"], correct:1, explanation:"Integration ensures risk informs strategic decisions. It does not guarantee zero losses or replace the board." },
  { id:40603, domain:3, level:1, question:"When a KRI consistently shows no variation over long periods, it may indicate the KRI is:", options:["Perfectly calibrated and well designed, and therefore it should never be changed or reviewed again","Clear evidence that the organization currently faces absolutely no risk of any kind whatsoever at all","Poorly designed or simply not sensitive enough to actually detect the relevant changes in the risk","A highly reliable lagging indicator that as a result requires no further periodic review or attention"], correct:2, explanation:"A flat KRI may be insensitive or poorly designed. Unchanging values rarely mean risk is truly absent." },
  { id:40604, domain:3, level:2, question:"Risk responses that introduce new risks should be:", options:["Implemented immediately without any further analysis simply because the original risk is reduced by it","Always automatically rejected outright, since any newly introduced risk is inherently unacceptable","Reported to management only after the secondary risk has already actually materialized into an event","Assessed for the secondary risks that they create before the chosen response is actually finalized"], correct:3, explanation:"Secondary risks must be assessed before finalizing the response. Ignoring them can worsen overall exposure." },
  { id:40605, domain:3, level:3, question:"The BEST indicator that a risk response has been successful is:", options:["The residual risk has been reduced to within the organization's defined acceptable risk appetite","The response was implemented exactly on the originally planned schedule and completion date target","The chosen response was the single least expensive option that was available at the time of selection","No one anywhere within the organization raised any objection at all to the chosen response option"], correct:0, explanation:"Success is measured by residual risk falling within appetite. On-time delivery alone does not prove success." },
  { id:40606, domain:3, level:2, question:"Periodic reassessment of accepted risks is necessary because acceptance is:", options:["Entirely permanent in nature and as a result never needs to be revisited again once it is approved","Valid only for as long as the underlying conditions and the original assumptions still continue to hold","Automatically converted into formal mitigation after a single fixed and predetermined period of time","A decision that only the internal audit function holds the authority to subsequently reverse or change overall"], correct:1, explanation:"Acceptance holds only while assumptions remain valid, requiring reassessment. It is not permanent." },
  { id:40607, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk treatment plan that lacks an assigned owner is MOST likely to:", options:["Be completed considerably faster due to the broadly shared collective sense of responsibility for it","Automatically escalate itself directly up to the board of directors for their own direct execution instead","Stall and fail to progress, because no single individual is actually accountable for executing the actions","Reduce the overall residual risk even without anyone at all actually taking any of the planned action"], correct:2, explanation:"Without an owner, the plan stalls from lack of accountability. Diffuse responsibility slows, not speeds, action." },
  { id:40608, domain:3, level:2, question:"Comparing residual risk against inherent risk helps demonstrate:", options:["That the controls are fundamentally unnecessary because some level of risk always exists regardless","That the organization should therefore always simply accept all of its inherent risk in every situation","The exact precise monetary cost of every single control that is deployed across the whole environment","The genuine value and the actual effectiveness that is being delivered by the implemented controls"], correct:3, explanation:"The inherent-to-residual reduction shows control value. It does not justify discarding controls or accepting all risk." },
  { id:40609, domain:3, level:1, question:"Which is the BEST practice when a control consistently fails its tests?", options:["Investigate the underlying root cause and then redesign or replace the consistently failing control","Continue to operate the control entirely unchanged and simply hope that future tests pass eventually","Immediately and formally accept all of the related risk without any further analysis being performed","Conceal the repeated failures so that the organization's control dashboard always remains fully green"], correct:0, explanation:"Repeated failures require root-cause analysis and redesign. Concealing or ignoring them leaves risk unmanaged." },
  { id:40610, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MOST important reason to keep the risk register and risk profile aligned is to:", options:["Reduce the total overall number of separate documents that the organization has to maintain at once overall","Ensure that the reported exposure accurately reflects the actual underlying details of the real risk","Allow the high-level risk profile to permanently replace the more detailed underlying risk register","Guarantee that no genuinely new risks will ever need to be added to either document again in future"], correct:1, explanation:"Alignment ensures reported exposure reflects reality. The profile summarizes but does not replace the register." },
  { id:40611, domain:3, level:3, question:"A control owner requesting an exception should be required to provide:", options:["A firm guarantee that the underlying risk will simply never materialize at all during the exception period","Approval that has been signed off on only by the requesting control owner entirely on their own behalf","A clear justification, the relevant compensating measures, and a defined remediation timeline for closure","Assurance that absolutely no ongoing monitoring will be needed at all during the entire exception period"], correct:2, explanation:"Exceptions need justification, compensating measures, and a remediation date. Self-approval lacks proper authority." },
  { id:40612, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which BEST describes the relationship between monitoring and reporting?", options:["Monitoring and reporting are fundamentally identical activities with no meaningful distinction at all","Reporting gathers all of the underlying data, while monitoring then communicates it to the board directly","Neither monitoring nor reporting is needed at all once the relevant controls have been implemented once","Monitoring gathers the risk and control data, which the subsequent reporting then communicates onward"], correct:3, explanation:"Monitoring collects data; reporting communicates it. They are complementary, not identical or interchangeable." },
  { id:40613, domain:3, level:1, question:"The PRIMARY reason third-party risk responses must be continuously monitored is that:", options:["A vendor's overall risk posture can meaningfully deteriorate over the life of the entire relationship","Vendors simply never change their underlying control environment at all after the initial onboarding","Continuous monitoring completely eliminates the future need for any contractual security terms at all","The act of continuous monitoring fully transfers all of the vendor's risk back to the vendor itself"], correct:0, explanation:"Vendor risk posture can degrade over time, so monitoring is ongoing. It does not transfer risk to the vendor." },
  { id:40614, domain:3, level:3, question:"When prioritizing which risks to respond to first, the organization should consider:", options:["The simple alphabetical ordering of the various risk names as they appear in the enterprise register","The level of each risk relative to the defined appetite together with its overall potential impact","Whichever of the various risks happen to be the cheapest and the easiest to fully remediate quickly","Only those particular risks that happen to have been most recently added to the register this period"], correct:1, explanation:"Prioritization is driven by risk level versus appetite and impact, not alphabetical order or ease alone." },
  { id:40615, domain:3, level:2, question:"A 'risk treatment owner' who lacks authority to allocate resources will likely:", options:["Complete the assigned treatment far more efficiently due to having considerably fewer distractions","Automatically gain all of the needed authority and resources the moment the treatment plan is approved","Struggle to actually execute the plan in practice, requiring an escalation in order to obtain support","Have no effect at all, either positive or negative, on the ultimate success of the treatment effort"], correct:2, explanation:"Without resource authority, the owner struggles and must escalate. Plan approval does not confer such authority." },
  { id:40616, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which is the STRONGEST form of evidence that a corrective control works?", options:["A formal written policy statement that simply asserts the corrective control does indeed exist in place","The control owner's general confidence and stated belief that the recovery process would likely succeed","The complete absence of any incident at all that would have actually required the control to be used","A demonstrated successful recovery achieved during a test exercise or an actual real-world incident"], correct:3, explanation:"Demonstrated successful recovery is strongest. Untested confidence and absence of incidents prove little." },
  { id:40617, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to report risk trends over time to the board is to:", options:["Show the changes in exposure across multiple periods measured against the defined appetite thresholds","Provide only the single most recent risk value point with no accompanying historical context at all","List every single individual log event that was captured throughout the entire reporting period in full","Report only those risks that improved over the period while quietly omitting any that actually worsened"], correct:0, explanation:"Trend reporting against thresholds reveals direction. Omitting worsening risks gives a misleading picture." },
  { id:40618, domain:3, level:1, question:"A compensating control should provide assurance that is:", options:["Completely unrelated to the original objective of the primary control it is meant to compensate for","Comparable to the objective that the missing or infeasible primary control would otherwise achieve","Always deliberately weaker than the primary control in order to meaningfully reduce its operating cost","Sufficient on its own to permanently remove the underlying risk entirely from the risk register fully"], correct:1, explanation:"Compensating controls meet a comparable objective to the primary. Unrelated assurance does not compensate." },
  { id:40619, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY purpose of escalation thresholds in risk monitoring is to:", options:["Ensure that all of the organization's risks are escalated up to the board regardless of their severity","Prevent any of the relevant risk information from ever reaching senior management at all going forward","Define clearly when a particular risk change warrants the attention of a higher level of authority","Completely replace the future need for any documented and formal risk treatment plan whatsoever"], correct:2, explanation:"Escalation thresholds define when higher attention is warranted. Escalating everything would overwhelm decision makers." },
  { id:40620, domain:3, level:2, question:"When the business context changes faster than controls can adapt, the organization should:", options:["Freeze all of the existing controls firmly in place and simply disregard the rapidly changing context","Permanently accept all of the relevant risk on the basis that any adaptation is simply too difficult now","Transfer the entire affected business operation to an external third-party provider to avoid the issue","Reassess the affected risks and then adjust the responses in order to match the new conditions present"], correct:3, explanation:"Changing context requires reassessing and adjusting responses. Freezing controls leaves emerging gaps unaddressed." },
  { id:40621, domain:3, level:2, question:"Including target dates and milestones in a treatment plan PRIMARILY supports:", options:["Effective tracking, clear accountability, and the timely completion of the planned remediation actions","The ongoing ability to indefinitely postpone the necessary remediation work without any consequence","The immediate formal closure of the underlying risk before any of the planned work has been performed overall","The complete elimination of any future need to monitor the ongoing progress of the treatment effort"], correct:0, explanation:"Dates and milestones enable tracking and timely completion. They support, not eliminate, progress monitoring." },
  { id:40622, domain:3, level:3, question:"The BEST description of 'risk culture' in the context of risk response is:", options:["The full set of automated technical controls that have been deployed across all of the firm's systems","Shared values and behaviors that shape how the people identify, assess, and respond to risk over time","The total annual budget that has been formally approved for the enterprise risk program's activities","The complete list of all of the regulators that currently supervise the organization's industry sector"], correct:1, explanation:"Risk culture is shared values and behavior around risk. It is not the control set or the program budget." },
  { id:40623, domain:3, level:1, question:"An effective risk reporting cadence should be:", options:["Kept completely identical for all of the risks regardless of their individual volatility or severity","Set as infrequent as is reasonably possible in order to minimize the overall reporting workload involved","Aligned to the risk velocity, the severity, and the actual decision needs of the relevant stakeholders","Determined solely on the basis of the personal convenience of the individual reporting risk analyst"], correct:2, explanation:"Cadence aligns to risk velocity and decision needs. A one-size cadence ignores differing risk dynamics." },
  { id:40624, domain:3, level:2, question:"A risk that exceeds appetite but cannot be feasibly mitigated should be:", options:["Silently left within the risk register entirely without ever informing the senior management about it","Automatically accepted by the risk practitioner entirely on their own without any escalation at all","Removed completely from the risk register simply on the basis that mitigation is not currently feasible","Escalated so that the organization's leadership can decide whether to accept, avoid, or transfer it"], correct:3, explanation:"Out-of-appetite, un-mitigable risk must be escalated for a leadership decision, not silently retained or accepted." },
  { id:40625, domain:3, level:3, question:"The MAIN benefit of standardizing risk register fields across the organization is to:", options:["Enable consistent aggregation, meaningful comparison, and reliable reporting of risks across the firm","Guarantee that every single recorded risk ends up with an exactly identical impact rating and level","Completely remove the ongoing need to assign any accountable owner to any of the recorded risks","Ensure that no genuinely new risk categories can ever be created or added at any point in the future overall"], correct:0, explanation:"Standard fields enable consistent aggregation and comparison. They do not equalize impact or remove ownership." },
  { id:40626, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which BEST supports a decision to retain (accept) a risk?", options:["The risk happens to be the single newest entry that was most recently added to the risk register","The cost of any further response clearly exceeds the benefit and the risk remains within the appetite","The control owner simply has a personal preference for not having to do any additional work on it","No direct competitor has yet chosen to actively respond to a broadly similar type of risk exposure overall"], correct:1, explanation:"Retention is justified when response cost exceeds benefit and risk is within appetite. Personal preference is not a basis." },
  { id:40627, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY reason to validate KRI data quality is that:", options:["Consistently high-quality data effectively guarantees that no risk event will ever actually occur again","Data quality becomes entirely irrelevant once a particular KRI has actually been initially defined once","Decisions that are based on inaccurate or unreliable indicator data can easily end up being misguided","Validated data completely removes the future need to set any thresholds for the KRI at all going forward"], correct:2, explanation:"Poor KRI data quality leads to misguided decisions, so validation matters. It does not prevent all events." },
  { id:40628, domain:3, level:2, question:"When multiple risk owners share a single cross-cutting risk, the BEST approach is to:", options:["Deliberately leave the accountability ambiguous so that each owner is free to act fully independently","Split the single risk into several unrelated fragments with no coordination between them at all afterward","Assign the entire shared risk completely to the internal audit function for them to take ongoing ownership","Designate a single primary accountable owner while still coordinating closely with all the others involved"], correct:3, explanation:"A designated primary owner with coordination prevents gaps. Ambiguous accountability leaves the risk unmanaged." },
  { id:40629, domain:3, level:1, question:"Reporting only aggregate green status while hiding underlying red items is problematic because it:", options:["Masks the material exposures from view and can therefore lead directly to poor management decisions","Genuinely improves the overall accuracy of management's understanding of the actual underlying risk","Is in fact the strongly recommended approach for designing all executive-level risk dashboards in use","Automatically and immediately reduces the organization's actual underlying residual risk exposure level"], correct:0, explanation:"Hiding red items behind green aggregates masks exposure and misleads decisions. It does not reduce real risk." },
  { id:40630, domain:3, level:2, question:"A newly deployed preventive control unexpectedly disrupts a business process. The BEST action is to:", options:["Remove the disruptive control entirely and then simply accept the original unmitigated underlying risk","Assess the trade-off involved and then tune the control to better balance the risk and the operations","Ignore the resulting disruption entirely on the basis that the control does reduce the targeted risk","Transfer the affected disrupted business process to a third party in order to avoid the issue entirely"], correct:1, explanation:"Tuning balances risk reduction and operations. Removing the control or ignoring disruption are both poor extremes." },
  { id:40631, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY reason to document control ownership in the risk register is to:", options:["Increase the overall length and the detail of the register specifically for the benefit of the auditors","Ensure that the affected controls can simply never be reassigned to any different owner again later on","Establish clear and unambiguous accountability for the control's ongoing operation and maintenance","Completely replace the future need to ever test the relevant controls for their ongoing effectiveness"], correct:2, explanation:"Documented ownership establishes accountability. It neither prevents reassignment nor replaces control testing." },
  { id:40632, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which is the BEST example of a corrective administrative control?", options:["A firewall rule configuration that blocks all unauthorized inbound network traffic at the perimeter","A securely locked cabinet that is used to safely secure the physical backup media within a facility","An intrusion detection system that automatically alerts the team on any anomalous network activity","A revised written procedure that is issued after an incident specifically to prevent its recurrence"], correct:3, explanation:"A revised post-incident procedure is corrective and administrative. The firewall and IDS are technical controls." },
  { id:40633, domain:3, level:1, question:"The BEST reason to align risk responses with strategic objectives is to:", options:["Ensure that the risk treatment actually supports, rather than unnecessarily hinders, the business goals","Ensure that the security team is able to operate fully independently of the wider business at all times","Guarantee that no individual business objective will ever introduce any genuinely new risk at any point","Allow the various risk responses to be freely selected without any cost consideration being made at all"], correct:0, explanation:"Aligning responses with strategy ensures they support business goals. It does not eliminate all new risk." },
  { id:40634, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk owner accepts a risk that actually exceeds their delegated authority. This is:", options:["Entirely acceptable, because in practice any manager may freely accept any level of risk they wish to overall","An improper acceptance that should therefore be escalated up to the appropriate higher authority level","A valid and complete transfer of the underlying risk directly to the acting manager's own department","A complete and effective avoidance of the underlying risk by the individual acting as the risk owner"], correct:1, explanation:"Acceptance beyond delegated authority is improper and must be escalated. It is neither a transfer nor avoidance." },
  { id:40635, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MOST useful way to present residual risk to executives is to show it:", options:["As a single undifferentiated total figure with no stated relation to the organization's risk appetite","Only for those particular risks that have already been fully and completely resolved and then closed","Relative to the defined risk appetite so that the executives can clearly see where action is needed","Buried deep within a lengthy technical appendix without any accompanying executive summary at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Showing residual risk against appetite highlights where action is needed. An appetite-blind total is less actionable." },
  { id:40636, domain:3, level:3, question:"Continuous improvement of the control environment relies MOST on:", options:["Implementing all of the controls one single time and then simply never revisiting any of them again","Deliberately avoiding all changes to the existing controls in order to maintain a fully stable environment","Transferring all of the various control responsibilities entirely to external third-party service providers","Using the feedback from ongoing monitoring, testing, and reporting in order to refine the controls"], correct:3, explanation:"Feedback from monitoring, testing, and reporting drives improvement. A static, never-revisited control set stagnates." },
  { id:40637, domain:3, level:2, question:"A KRI that lags far behind actual risk changes is problematic because it:", options:["Detects the relevant changes in risk too late to actually enable any timely preventive action to be taken","Provides considerably earlier warning of a change than any corresponding leading indicator possibly could","Is always demonstrably more accurate in every situation than any corresponding available leading indicator","Completely removes the future need for the organization to define and set any thresholds for the KRI at all"], correct:0, explanation:"A lagging KRI detects change too late for timely action. Lagging does not make it more accurate or earlier." },
  { id:40638, domain:3, level:1, question:"The risk practitioner should ensure that risk responses are:", options:["Selected and then formally approved entirely without ever involving any of the affected risk owners at all","Documented, formally approved by the owners, and then tracked through to their completion over time","Implemented quietly in secret in order to deliberately avoid drawing any attention from the auditors","Closed and signed off immediately upon their initial selection without any actual implementation at all"], correct:1, explanation:"Responses should be documented, owner-approved, and tracked to completion. Excluding owners undermines accountability." },
  { id:40639, domain:3, level:3, question:"When a third party suffers a breach, the organization should FIRST:", options:["Simply assume that its own data is entirely unaffected and as a result take no action whatsoever at all","Immediately and very publicly blame the third party entirely for causing the whole of the breach itself","Assess the potential impact of the breach on its own data and then invoke the relevant response plans","Delete all of its records of the third-party relationship in order to limit its own potential liability"], correct:2, explanation:"The organization first assesses impact on its own data and responds. Assuming no impact risks missing exposure." },
  { id:40640, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MAIN purpose of a risk and control matrix (RACM) is to:", options:["Completely replace the entire enterprise risk register with a single large static spreadsheet document","List only those specific controls that have recently failed during the most recent rounds of testing","Record and store the personal annual performance ratings of each of the individual employees involved","Map the risks to their corresponding controls, owners, and testing in order to provide clear oversight"], correct:3, explanation:"A RACM maps risks to controls, owners, and testing. It complements, not replaces, the risk register." },
  { id:40641, domain:3, level:2, question:"Effective risk response monitoring should trigger reassessment when:", options:["A significant change in the threat landscape, the controls, or the business context actually occurs","The ongoing monitoring simply confirms that everything is currently operating exactly as was expected","An external auditor has not specifically requested any updates at all during the current reporting year","The relevant risk has remained completely and entirely unchanged for several consecutive years running"], correct:0, explanation:"Significant change triggers reassessment. Stable, as-expected operation does not by itself require it." },
  { id:40642, domain:3, level:3, question:"Reporting near-misses (events that almost caused harm) is valuable because it:", options:["Definitively proves that the organization's various controls have now all failed completely and entirely","Surfaces the emerging underlying weaknesses early, before they actually cause a real and material loss","Completely eliminates the future need to monitor any of the controls at all for the remainder of the year","Automatically transfers the underlying risk that caused the near-miss directly to an external third party"], correct:1, explanation:"Near-miss reporting surfaces weaknesses before real loss occurs. It does not prove total control failure." },
  { id:40643, domain:3, level:1, question:"The BEST way to ensure exception decisions are consistent is to:", options:["Let each individual manager freely apply their own personal criteria entirely independently each time","Approve all of the requested exceptions automatically and without review in order to save valuable time overall","Apply a clearly defined exception process with set criteria and the appropriate authority levels involved","Reject all of the submitted exception requests outright regardless of any business justification given"], correct:2, explanation:"A defined process with criteria and authority ensures consistency. Ad hoc personal criteria produce inconsistency." },
  { id:40644, domain:3, level:2, question:"A control designed to detect AND alert on policy violations is BEST classified as:", options:["A purely preventive control, since its main role is to actively block the violations before they occur","A corrective control, since its main role is to restore the affected system after a violation takes place","A physical control, since its primary role is to secure the relevant facility against any intruders present","A detective control, since its primary role is to identify the violations after they have already happened"], correct:3, explanation:"Detecting and alerting is a detective control. Preventive controls block, and corrective controls restore." },
  { id:40645, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY goal of communicating residual risk to risk owners is to:", options:["Enable the owners to make properly informed decisions about acceptance or any further needed action","Deliberately shift all of the blame for any future incident squarely onto the relevant risk owners","Satisfy a formal internal requirement to generate the maximum possible number of reports each period","Completely remove the future need for the risk practitioner to ever monitor the relevant risk again"], correct:0, explanation:"Communicating residual risk enables informed owner decisions. It is not about blame or ending monitoring." },
  { id:40646, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which factor MOST increases the priority of responding to a given risk?", options:["The risk happens to be described using particularly specialized and highly technical terminology in it overall","The risk's actual exposure level substantially exceeds the organization's clearly defined risk appetite","The risk was added to the enterprise register personally by a fairly senior and well-known executive","The risk simply has a considerably longer written description than the other entries in the register"], correct:1, explanation:"Exposure exceeding appetite drives response priority. Wording, author, or length do not determine urgency." },
  { id:40647, domain:3, level:3, question:"A 'risk treatment plan' differs from a 'risk response' in that the plan:", options:["Is the high-level conceptual choice itself, while the response is only ever theoretical and abstract","Completely replaces the future need to ever actually choose a particular risk response option at all","Operationalizes the chosen response into the specific actions, the assigned owners, and the due dates","Applies only to those particular risks that the organization has already decided to fully and entirely avoid"], correct:2, explanation:"The plan operationalizes the chosen response into actions. The response is the strategic choice; the plan executes it." },
  { id:40648, domain:3, level:1, question:"Periodic independent validation of self-assessed controls is important because:", options:["A control self-assessment is always perfectly objective and is therefore never biased in any way at all","Independent validation completely removes the future need to perform any self-assessment at all going forward","External validation conveniently transfers all of the underlying control risk directly to the validating party","Self-assessments may sometimes be overly optimistic and can therefore benefit from independent checking"], correct:3, explanation:"Self-assessments can be optimistic, so independent validation adds objectivity. It complements, not replaces, CSA." },
  { id:40649, domain:3, level:2, question:"When risk exposure decreases below appetite due to external factors, the organization should:", options:["Verify that the observed change is genuinely durable before reducing any of the related controls in place","Immediately remove all of the related controls in order to cut the recurring operating costs involved","Simply assume that the observed reduction is entirely permanent and then stop monitoring the risk fully","Increase the relevant controls still further despite the now meaningfully reduced exposure level present overall"], correct:0, explanation:"Verify the reduction is durable before relaxing controls. Assuming permanence and dropping monitoring is risky." },
  { id:40650, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MOST appropriate metric to track remediation of overdue risk actions is a:", options:["Simple count of the total number of employees across the entire organization during the current year","Trend of the number of overdue treatment actions together with their aging over a period of time","Measure of the total overall revenue that was generated by the whole business during this past quarter","Complete list of all of the various vendors that the organization currently has under active contract"], correct:1, explanation:"Overdue-action aging trends track remediation health. Headcount and revenue are unrelated to remediation status." },
  { id:40651, domain:3, level:3, question:"A control that has become obsolete due to a process change should be:", options:["Retained completely unchanged indefinitely simply in order to preserve a sense of historical continuity","Immediately and entirely deleted from all of the records without any accompanying documentation at all","Reviewed and then either formally retired or replaced so that it properly matches the current process","Transferred over to an external third party in order for them to continue operating it externally instead"], correct:2, explanation:"Obsolete controls should be reviewed and retired or replaced. Retaining them wastes effort and may mislead." },
  { id:40652, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to ensure accountability for accepted risks is to:", options:["Deliberately leave the acceptances unsigned so that the responsibility instead remains shared broadly","Allow all of the various acceptances to be approved purely verbally and without any documentation at all","Delegate all of the risk acceptance decisions entirely to the organization's internal audit function instead","Record a clearly named approver, the underlying rationale, and a defined expiry for each acceptance"], correct:3, explanation:"Named approver, rationale, and expiry create accountability. Unsigned or verbal acceptances leave it unclear." },
  { id:40653, domain:3, level:1, question:"Which BEST demonstrates that risk reporting is influencing decisions?", options:["Management actively allocates resources and adjusts the responses based directly on the reports received","The various reports are simply filed away and archived without any subsequent follow-up actions taken","The risk reports are consistently the single longest documents that are produced by the organization","The reports are distributed widely to the maximum possible number of individual recipients each period overall"], correct:0, explanation:"Resource allocation and response changes show influence. Filing reports without action shows none." },
  { id:40654, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk response should be revisited when a related control's effectiveness declines because:", options:["A declining level of control effectiveness has no bearing at all on the resulting residual risk exposure","Reduced control effectiveness can in turn raise the resulting residual risk above the defined appetite","The controls in question will automatically recover their lost effectiveness entirely without intervention","The residual risk is permanently fixed once a particular risk response has been initially selected for it"], correct:1, explanation:"Declining control effectiveness can push residual risk above appetite, so the response is revisited." },
  { id:40655, domain:3, level:2, question:"The PRIMARY reason to involve business stakeholders in control design is to:", options:["Deliberately slow the whole design process down so that even more committees can review all of the work","Conveniently transfer the accountability for the control's potential future failure onto the business itself","Ensure that the resulting controls are practical, effective, and accepted by those who are affected by them","Avoid having to actually test the resulting control at all once it has been fully implemented in production"], correct:2, explanation:"Stakeholder involvement makes controls practical and accepted. It is not about transferring blame or skipping testing." },
  { id:40656, domain:3, level:3, question:"When a risk's likelihood and impact both increase, the organization should:", options:["Simply maintain the existing risk response entirely unchanged regardless of the observed increase in risk","Automatically accept the now considerably higher risk level without performing any further review of it","Remove the affected risk entirely from the register on the basis that it has now changed in its nature","Reassess whether the current response still keeps the resulting risk within the defined risk appetite"], correct:3, explanation:"Increased likelihood and impact warrant reassessing the response against appetite. Keeping it unchanged ignores the shift." },
  { id:40657, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST description of a 'lagging' control metric is one that:", options:["Reports the actual control performance only after the relevant period or the event has already concluded","Reliably predicts any potential control failures well before they have any actual chance to occur at all","Always provides considerably earlier warning of an issue than any corresponding leading control metric does","Cannot be used in any form whatsoever within any of the organization's management risk reporting outputs"], correct:0, explanation:"Lagging metrics report after the fact. Leading metrics, not lagging ones, provide early warning." },
  { id:40658, domain:3, level:1, question:"The risk owner should communicate accepted risks to relevant stakeholders so that:", options:["The various stakeholders can then override the formal acceptance even without holding the proper authority","The affected parties are made fully aware of, and are properly prepared for, the retained risk exposure","The formal acceptance thereby becomes entirely permanent and as a result never requires any review again","The risk practitioner is then able to simply delete the accepted risk entirely from the register afterward"], correct:1, explanation:"Communicating acceptances ensures affected parties are aware and prepared. Acceptance still requires periodic review." },
  { id:40659, domain:3, level:3, question:"A control mapped to multiple regulatory requirements is valuable because it:", options:["Effectively guarantees the organization's full and complete compliance with every law in every jurisdiction","Completely eliminates the future need to actually test that control at all for its operating effectiveness","Efficiently addresses several distinct regulatory obligations through a single coordinated control effort","Conveniently removes the standing requirement to assign any accountable owner at all to that one control"], correct:2, explanation:"One control covering multiple requirements is efficient. It does not guarantee total compliance or skip testing." },
  { id:40660, domain:3, level:2, question:"When reporting risk to a technical team versus the board, the practitioner should:", options:["Use exactly the same identical level of detailed technical depth for both of the two distinct audiences","Provide the board of directors with considerably more raw technical log data than the technical team gets","Withhold all of the relevant risk information entirely from the technical team for security reasons alone","Adjust both the depth and the framing in order to properly match each audience's actual decision needs"], correct:3, explanation:"Framing should match each audience. The board needs business framing; the technical team needs operational detail." },
  { id:40661, domain:3, level:2, question:"A risk response plan with no link to measurable outcomes is problematic because:", options:["The actual success of the plan simply cannot be objectively evaluated at all without measurable outcomes","It conveniently allows the resulting progress and the effectiveness to be very easily demonstrated later","Measurable outcomes of any kind are in fact strictly forbidden in any form of risk treatment planning","The plan automatically reduces the resulting residual risk fully even without any measurement at all of it"], correct:0, explanation:"Without measurable outcomes, success cannot be objectively evaluated. Measures are essential, not forbidden." },
  { id:40662, domain:3, level:3, question:"The MOST important consideration when retiring a control is to confirm:", options:["That the affected control had a sufficiently memorable name within the organization's control catalog list overall","That the risk which the control originally addressed is no longer present or is otherwise covered elsewhere","That the affected control was indeed the single most expensive control in the entire operating environment","That no individual employee within the organization will actually object to that control being retired now"], correct:1, explanation:"Before retiring a control, confirm the risk is gone or otherwise covered. Naming and cost are irrelevant here." },
  { id:40663, domain:3, level:1, question:"A spike in a detective control's alert volume should PROMPT the practitioner to:", options:["Immediately disable the affected control in order to simply stop all of the alerts from being generated","Ignore all of the resulting alerts entirely on the basis that detective controls are not really actionable","Investigate carefully whether the organization's actual underlying risk exposure has genuinely increased","Immediately and formally accept all of the related underlying risk without any investigation being done"], correct:2, explanation:"An alert spike prompts investigation of possible increased exposure. Disabling the control would hide real risk." },
  { id:40664, domain:3, level:2, question:"The PRIMARY reason to assign clear authority levels for risk acceptance is to:", options:["Allow essentially any employee at all to freely accept a risk of any magnitude whatsoever entirely at will","Completely remove the standing requirement to ever document any of the risk acceptance decisions at all","Guarantee in practice that no risk of any kind will ever actually be accepted by the organization at all","Ensure that the various risks are only ever accepted by those who actually hold the appropriate authority"], correct:3, explanation:"Authority levels ensure acceptance happens at the right level. Without them, oversized risks could be wrongly accepted." },
  { id:40665, domain:3, level:3, question:"Which is the BEST example of a preventive administrative control?", options:["A segregation-of-duties policy that prevents any one single person from holding full end-to-end control","A formal backup restoration procedure that is executed only after an actual data loss event has occurred","A camera surveillance system that continuously records all of the activity within a sensitive work area","A firewall rule configuration that actively blocks all of the unauthorized inbound network connections"], correct:0, explanation:"Segregation-of-duties policy is preventive and administrative. Backups are corrective; firewalls are technical." },
  { id:40666, domain:3, level:2, question:"Tracking the time between control failure and detection helps the organization to:", options:["Completely eliminate the entire possibility of any of the controls ever failing again in the future at all","Assess the detective control effectiveness and thereby reduce the overall window of exposure to the risk","Conveniently transfer the entire detection responsibility itself directly over to an external third party","Completely remove the future need to operate any of the various preventive controls at all going forward"], correct:1, explanation:"Shorter failure-to-detection time reflects detective effectiveness. It does not eliminate failures or replace prevention." },
  { id:40667, domain:3, level:3, question:"When an accepted risk's expiry date passes without review, the organization should:", options:["Simply assume that the original acceptance automatically remains fully valid indefinitely from that point","Permanently delete the affected risk entirely from the register because the acceptance has now expired","Reassess the underlying risk and then either renew, revise, or otherwise treat the lapsed acceptance","Transfer the expired acceptance decision directly over to the organization's audit committee to handle"], correct:2, explanation:"An expired acceptance must be reassessed and renewed, revised, or treated. It does not auto-renew or auto-delete." },
  { id:40668, domain:3, level:1, question:"The MOST effective risk response programs ensure that responses are:", options:["Decided entirely centrally with no input at all sought from any of the affected business areas involved","Documented just one single time at the very start and then never actually reviewed again afterward at all","Selected purely and solely on the basis of the single lowest possible upfront implementation cost available","Owned, resourced, monitored, and reported on throughout their entire lifecycle from start to finish"], correct:3, explanation:"Effective responses are owned, resourced, monitored, and reported over their life, not decided once and abandoned." },
  { id:40669, domain:3, level:2, question:"A risk register that captures only IT risks is limited because it:", options:["Omits the operational, the strategic, and the various other risks that meaningfully affect the enterprise","Provides a genuinely complete enterprise-wide view of all of the organizational risk that actually exists","Effectively guarantees that no non-IT risk of any kind will ever actually affect the organization at all","Automatically and completely covers all of the third-party and the regulatory risks by default already"], correct:0, explanation:"An IT-only register omits broader enterprise risks. It does not provide a complete or all-encompassing view." },
  { id:40670, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST measure of whether a risk response improved the organization's posture is:", options:["The total overall number of individual pages that were contained in the documented risk response plan","A clear and demonstrable reduction in the resulting residual risk down toward the acceptable target levels","The relative seniority of the particular executive who originally approved the formal risk response plan overall","The total overall amount of money that was actually spent on implementing the chosen response option"], correct:1, explanation:"Posture improvement is shown by reduced residual risk. Plan length, approver seniority, and spend do not prove it." },
  { id:40671, domain:3, level:3, question:"Reporting that risk is 'fully eliminated' after mitigation is usually inaccurate because:", options:["Mitigation activity will in fact always reliably remove a full one hundred percent of every exposure present","Mitigation activity actually has no real effect whatsoever on the underlying level of risk in any situation","Some level of residual risk almost always still remains in place even after a mitigating control is applied","Any risk that has been eliminated must always first be formally transferred to an external third party"], correct:2, explanation:"Mitigation reduces but rarely eliminates risk, so residual risk remains. Claiming full elimination is misleading." },
  { id:40672, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a critical control depends on a single individual, the organization should:", options:["Simply accept the resulting dependency on the basis that the individual involved is particularly highly skilled","Ignore the underlying dependency entirely on the basis that the control currently operates perfectly well","Transfer the affected control entirely over into the individual employee's own personal ongoing ownership","Address the resulting key-person risk through deliberate cross-training or by building in some redundancy"], correct:3, explanation:"Key-person dependency is addressed via cross-training or redundancy. Relying on one person leaves a single point of failure." },
  { id:40673, domain:3, level:1, question:"The PRIMARY reason to reconcile reported risks with the underlying register is to:", options:["Ensure that the various reports accurately reflect the genuine current state of all of the recorded risks","Increase the total overall number of separate documents that then require a management signature each time","Allow the published report to permanently replace and supersede whatever figures appear in the register","Guarantee in practice that no discrepancies of any kind will ever actually arise again at any point in future"], correct:0, explanation:"Reconciliation ensures reports reflect the register's current state. The report does not supersede the register." },
  { id:40674, domain:3, level:3, question:"A control with high false-positive rates should be:", options:["Simply left entirely unchanged on the basis that essentially any alerting at all is inherently beneficial","Tuned in order to improve its accuracy and thereby reduce the resulting wasted investigative effort","Immediately removed altogether so that no further alerts of any kind are ever generated by it again","Accepted entirely as-is on the basis that false positives genuinely carry no real operational cost at all"], correct:1, explanation:"High false positives should be tuned for accuracy. Removing the control entirely would lose its detective value." },
  { id:40675, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to ensure that risk responses remain aligned with appetite over time is to:", options:["Set the risk appetite just one single time and then never compare any responses against it again at all","Allow each individual risk owner to freely define their own appetite for their own individual assigned risks","Periodically compare the residual risk and the responses against the organization's current appetite","Treat the risk appetite as being effectively identical to the maximum possible single-event loss amount"], correct:2, explanation:"Periodic comparison against current appetite keeps responses aligned. A one-time check ignores evolving appetite." },
  { id:40676, domain:3, level:3, question:"When documenting a risk response decision, it is MOST important to capture:", options:["The particular brand of coffee that happened to be served at the meeting where the decision was made","The exact precise seating arrangement of all of the members of the decision-making committee involved overall","The total overall word count of all of the supporting analysis documentation that was prepared for it","The underlying rationale, the expected resulting residual risk, the assigned owner, and the approval given"], correct:3, explanation:"Rationale, residual risk, owner, and approval are essential. Irrelevant meeting details add no value to the record." },
  { id:40677, domain:3, level:2, question:"Which is the BEST indicator that exception management is working effectively?", options:["The exceptions are time-bound, are actively tracked, and are then remediated by their assigned due dates","The various exceptions are allowed to accumulate indefinitely with no remediation activity at all on them","The exceptions can be freely approved by essentially anyone at all without any regard to authority levels","The exceptions are simply granted on a fully permanent basis so that they never need to be revisited again"], correct:0, explanation:"Time-bound, tracked, remediated exceptions show effective management. Accumulating, permanent exceptions show the opposite." },
  { id:40678, domain:3, level:1, question:"A risk response that addresses symptoms but not root cause will likely:", options:["Permanently and fully resolve the entire underlying risk with absolutely no recurrence of it ever again","Allow the underlying risk to recur over time because its actual root cause still remains entirely unaddressed","Have no real effect at all, in either direction, on the eventual recurrence of the underlying risk at all overall","Automatically eliminate the entire future need for any ongoing monitoring of the affected risk altogether"], correct:1, explanation:"Treating symptoms without root cause lets the risk recur. Addressing root cause is needed for lasting resolution." },
  { id:40679, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY purpose of trend analysis in risk monitoring is to:", options:["Capture only a single point-in-time snapshot of the risk with no surrounding historical context at all to it","Completely replace the standing need to define any KRIs at all for the organization at any point going forward","Reveal both the direction and the velocity of the organization's changing risk exposure over a period of time","Guarantee in practice that the organization's risk will reliably always decrease in every single future period"], correct:2, explanation:"Trend analysis reveals direction and velocity of risk change. A single snapshot lacks that temporal insight." },
  { id:40680, domain:3, level:2, question:"When residual risk consistently sits just below appetite, the organization should:", options:["Simply assume that no further attention of any kind is ever going to be needed for that particular risk again","Immediately remove all of the related controls already in place on the basis that the risk is now acceptable","Increase the defined risk appetite itself so that the residual risk then appears comfortably lower against it","Continue to monitor the risk closely, since even relatively small changes could end up breaching the appetite"], correct:3, explanation:"Risk near the appetite boundary warrants close monitoring. Removing controls or inflating appetite is unwise." },
  { id:40681, domain:3, level:2, question:"The MOST appropriate response when a regulator introduces a new mandatory control is to:", options:["Implement the newly required mandatory control and then update both the risk profile and the register","Accept the resulting risk of regulatory non-compliance rather than actually implementing the new control","Avoid the regulator's jurisdiction entirely by ceasing all of the related operations within that area at once","Transfer the entire compliance obligation itself directly over to an external cyber insurance provider instead"], correct:0, explanation:"Mandatory controls are implemented and reflected in the profile/register. Accepting non-compliance is not viable." },
  { id:40682, domain:3, level:3, question:"A risk treatment action marked complete should still be:", options:["Removed entirely from any further monitoring on the basis that the relevant action is now fully finished","Validated in order to confirm that it actually achieved the originally intended reduction in the risk level","Simply assumed to be fully effective without any independent verification at all of the resulting outcome overall","Reopened again indefinitely regardless of its actual genuine completion status as it currently stands now"], correct:1, explanation:"Completed actions are validated to confirm the intended reduction. Assuming effectiveness without checking is risky." },
  { id:40683, domain:3, level:1, question:"The BEST way to handle conflicting risk information from different sources is to:", options:["Always simply trust whichever happens to be the single most recent source and then discard all earlier data","Report all of the various conflicting figures together without any attempt at all being made to reconcile them","Reconcile the various conflicting sources and then validate them in order to establish an accurate picture","Select whichever single figure happens to make the overall risk appear to be the least severe to the reader"], correct:2, explanation:"Reconciling and validating conflicting sources yields accuracy. Picking the least severe figure distorts reporting." },
  { id:40684, domain:3, level:2, question:"The PRIMARY benefit of a centralized risk reporting platform is that it:", options:["Conveniently eliminates the entire future need for any of the risk owners to actually make any decisions","Effectively guarantees in practice that every single one of the reported risks will then be fully remediated","Completely removes the standing requirement to ever validate any of the underlying reported risk data","Provides consistent, timely, and properly consolidated risk information across the whole organization"], correct:3, explanation:"Centralized reporting gives consistent, consolidated information. It does not replace owner decisions or data validation." },
  { id:40685, domain:3, level:3, question:"When the organization's risk appetite changes, the practitioner should:", options:["Reassess all of the existing responses in order to ensure their continued alignment with the new appetite","Simply leave all of the various existing responses entirely unchanged regardless of the new appetite level","Delete all of the current risks entirely and then rebuild the entire risk register again from scratch fully","Treat the change in the risk appetite as being effectively irrelevant to any operational risk responses at all"], correct:0, explanation:"An appetite change requires reassessing responses for alignment. Leaving them unchanged risks misalignment." },
  { id:40686, domain:3, level:2, question:"A control that is technically effective but creates excessive operational friction should be:", options:["Retained entirely unchanged on the basis that its underlying technical effectiveness is all that truly matters","Evaluated carefully in order to find a better overall balance between the risk reduction and the usability","Removed altogether and entirely so that the original underlying risk is then simply left fully unmitigated","Transferred over to an external third party for them to operate it without any modification at all to it"], correct:1, explanation:"Such a control should be rebalanced for usability. Ignoring friction or removing it outright are poor extremes." },
  { id:40687, domain:3, level:3, question:"The MOST important reason to keep risk owners informed of monitoring results is to:", options:["Generate the single largest possible volume of internal status update emails across the whole organization","Conveniently transfer all of the ongoing monitoring responsibility itself directly onto the risk owners","Enable the owners to make timely decisions whenever the monitoring reveals a genuine change in exposure","Completely remove the risk practitioner's own involvement in the affected risk going forward entirely"], correct:2, explanation:"Informing owners of monitoring results enables timely decisions. It is not about email volume or shedding responsibility." },
  { id:40688, domain:3, level:1, question:"A risk response that satisfies compliance but leaves real exposure should prompt the practitioner to:", options:["Consider the underlying risk to now be fully and completely addressed simply because compliance was achieved","Remove the affected risk entirely from the register on the basis that the regulatory requirement is now met","Transfer the resulting residual exposure that remains directly over to the organization's compliance department","Highlight the remaining real exposure that still exists and then recommend appropriate further treatment of it"], correct:3, explanation:"Compliance alone may leave real exposure; the practitioner highlights it. Checking the compliance box is not enough." },
  { id:40689, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to validate that a transferred risk is genuinely covered is to:", options:["Review the actual terms carefully in order to confirm the real scope and the limits of the risk transfer itself","Simply assume that the relevant contract or insurance policy fully covers every conceivable possible scenario","Rely solely and entirely on the counterparty's verbal assurance that the relevant risk is indeed fully covered overall","Remove the affected risk entirely from the register the moment that the relevant contract has been signed off"], correct:0, explanation:"Reviewing terms confirms what is actually covered. Assuming full coverage or relying on verbal claims is risky." },
  { id:40690, domain:3, level:2, question:"A risk practitioner observes controls operating well but residual risk still above appetite. This suggests:", options:["That the relevant controls are clearly unnecessary and should therefore simply be removed altogether at once","That the current set of controls is insufficient and therefore additional risk response is genuinely needed","That the residual risk should now simply be accepted as it stands regardless of the defined risk appetite level","That the organization's risk appetite must be wrong and so it should simply be raised in order to match it up"], correct:1, explanation:"If well-operating controls still leave risk above appetite, more response is needed, not removal or appetite inflation." },
  { id:40691, domain:3, level:3, question:"The PRIMARY reason to report both KRIs and KCIs together is to:", options:["Provide deliberately redundant data points that will always end up saying the exact same thing each time","Completely replace the future need for any narrative explanation at all of the various reported risks involved","Show both the changing risk exposure and also whether the relevant controls are actually still holding up","Effectively guarantee in practice that no risk event of any kind at all will occur in the upcoming period"], correct:2, explanation:"KRIs show exposure changes and KCIs show control health; together they give a fuller picture. They are not redundant." },
  { id:40692, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a business unit resists implementing an approved risk response, the practitioner should:", options:["Simply abandon the approved response altogether on the basis that the business unit declined to cooperate with it","Implement the approved response entirely covertly and quietly without ever informing the affected business unit","Remove the affected underlying risk entirely from the register in order to simply avoid the conflict altogether","Escalate the matter to the appropriate level of management in order to resolve the implementation gap that exists"], correct:3, explanation:"Resistance to an approved response is escalated for resolution. Abandoning or hiding the response leaves risk unaddressed." },
  { id:40693, domain:3, level:1, question:"The MOST effective risk treatment plans assign actions that are:", options:["Specific, measurable, time-bound, and clearly assigned to a properly accountable individual action owner","Deliberately vague and open-ended in nature so that the assigned owners retain maximum flexibility forever","Made entirely identical for every single risk regardless of that risk's actual individual nature or its severity","Determined exclusively and solely on the basis of the single lowest-cost available option in every single case"], correct:0, explanation:"Specific, measurable, time-bound, owned actions drive execution. Vague open-ended actions rarely get completed." },
  { id:40694, domain:3, level:3, question:"A sudden drop in a detective control's alerts could indicate:", options:["That the affected control is now definitely and clearly functioning even better than it ever was before this","That the affected control may have actually failed and so is no longer detecting any of the relevant events","That the underlying risk has now been entirely and permanently eliminated from the whole environment fully","That the affected control should now simply be expanded further in order to generate even more alerts still"], correct:1, explanation:"A sudden alert drop may mean the control has failed silently, not that risk vanished. It warrants investigation." },
  { id:40695, domain:3, level:2, question:"The BEST way to ensure risk reporting supports accountability is to:", options:["Report all of the various risks consistently without ever naming any owners or any required actions for them","Aggregate all of the individual risks together so that no single risk can ever be traced back to any one owner","Clearly identify the relevant owners, the required actions, and the due dates for each reported risk entry","Distribute all of the resulting reports entirely anonymously with no attribution of any kind included at all"], correct:2, explanation:"Naming owners, actions, and due dates supports accountability. Ownerless, anonymous reporting undermines it." },
  { id:40696, domain:3, level:3, question:"When evaluating whether to accept, mitigate, transfer, or avoid, the practitioner should:", options:["Always simply default to the acceptance option as being the single simplest one that is available to choose","Choose whichever single response option the organization's current IT vendor most strongly recommends to it","Select whichever of the various available options happens to require the very least documentation effort overall overall","Compare each available option's relative cost, its resulting residual risk, and its overall fit with the appetite"], correct:3, explanation:"Each option is compared on cost, residual risk, and appetite fit. Defaulting to acceptance ignores better options." },
  { id:40697, domain:3, level:2, question:"The PRIMARY reason to document compensating controls for an exception is to:", options:["Show that the resulting residual risk is genuinely reduced during the entire period of the active exception","Make the underlying exception fully permanent so that it then never actually requires any further review again","Conveniently avoid having to assign any accountable owner or any defined expiry date at all to the exception","Completely eliminate the future need to ever actually remediate the underlying control gap that still exists"], correct:0, explanation:"Compensating controls show residual risk is reduced while the gap is open. The gap still needs remediation." },
  { id:40698, domain:3, level:1, question:"An organization's overall residual risk trending upward over several quarters should prompt:", options:["No action of any kind at all, since quarter-to-quarter variation in the figures is always entirely meaningless","An investigation into the underlying drivers along with a review of the overall adequacy of the responses","The immediate and formal acceptance of the now higher risk level in order to simply avoid any further analysis","The removal of the observed trend itself from the reports in order to keep the dashboards looking nice and stable"], correct:1, explanation:"An upward residual-risk trend warrants investigating drivers and response adequacy, not hiding the trend." },
  { id:40699, domain:3, level:3, question:"The BEST reason to maintain version history of the risk register is to:", options:["Deliberately increase the overall storage cost of actually maintaining the risk register itself over the years","Effectively prevent any future updates of any kind from ever being made again to the risk register going forward","Provide a clear audit trail of exactly how the various risks and responses have changed over a period of time","Completely replace the standing need to ever assign any current accountable owners to any of the recorded risks"], correct:2, explanation:"Version history provides an audit trail of changes. It neither blocks updates nor removes the need for ownership." },
  { id:40700, domain:3, level:2, question:"When a risk response is delegated to a third party, the organization should retain:", options:["Absolutely no oversight whatsoever at all once the relevant delegation to the party has been fully completed","Only the financial cost of the activity itself while fully abandoning all accountability for the actual results","The standing right to simply ignore the third party's actual ongoing performance of the response entirely","Sufficient oversight in order to verify that the third party actually performs the agreed response effectively"], correct:3, explanation:"Delegation requires retained oversight to verify performance. Accountability for outcomes stays with the organization." },
];
